'''Gustav Klimt''' was an Austrian symbolist painter and one of the most prominent members of the [[Vienna]] Secession movement. His primary subject was the female body, and his works are marked by a frank eroticism and an ornamental, often gilded surface treatment drawn from Byzantine mosaics.

His "Golden Phase" produced his most celebrated works, including "[[The Kiss]]" and the "Portrait of Adele Bloch-Bauer I", which combine richly patterned decoration with naturalistic figures and have become enduring icons of early twentieth-century art.
